Updated for [b]1.7.0[/b]

aka "Unfinished Business"...
*Though the "Business" is "Unfinished", the [b]mod itself is[/b] in fact [b]Finished[/b].

[h1][i]Saddened by your best friend's indifference towards your heir?[/i][/h1]

This mod enables the possibility of an heir to [b]inherit their predecessors' relations[/b] when the time comes.
Now taking a crown comes with its unique [b]diplomatic benefits and challenges[/b], depending on the previous holder's relations and how close you two are related.

[img]https://imgur.com/p7Fv1Z6.gif[/img]

[h1][b]🩸 Cross-Generational Friends & Rivals[/b][/h1]
A character's friend will be marked as a [b]potential friend[/b] of your heir after succession, along with a [b]+30 opinion boost[/b]. 
They would be much more likely to become friends assuming they don't have a particularly bad relationship prior to the succession.
While certainly not guaranteed, with some effort and luck, one could maintain friendships between two lineages for several generations. 
The same goes for the [b]predecessor's rivals[/b] (Marked as [b]potential rivals[/b] with a [b]-30 opinion penalty[/b])

Note: only the [b]primary heir[/b] of a character will inherit their relations. A character can only get their relations inherited [b]once per lifetime[/b]. However, one could inherit the relations of [b]multiple predecessors[/b].
All opinion modifier, positive or negative, lasts for [b]10 years[/b] (values decays over time)

[h1][b]🤝🏼 Life-Long Relations[/b] have [b]Larger Impacts[/b][/h1]
Best friends and nemesis are much rarer than their ordinary counterparts (In vanilla, Less than 5% of friends will later become best friends). Thus, it is only fair for the characters involved to value these special relations more.
A character's [b]Best Friend[/b] will become the [b]friend[/b] of their heir after succession, provided they don't have a particularly bad prior relationship (E.g. rivalry or opinions lower than -30).
If they cannot become friends because their opinions of each other are too low, they will become [b]potential friends[/b] instead. (Along with a mutual [b]+60 opinion boost[/b] to help them get along)
The same logic is also applied to [b]nemesis[/b], just the negative version.

*Only adult heirs can directly inherit friendships (become friends on succession) to simulate child heirs' lack of exposure to the relations of their predecessors
*Direct inheritance of friendship can be turned off in Game Rules if you feel it's not balanced due to Ritualized Friendship tradition.

[h1]🔗 [b]Tiered Inheritance Rules[/b] based on [b]Predecessor-Heir[/b] relation[/h1] 
[b]Not all heirs are judged equally[/b]. The rules stated above [b]only apply[/b] to those who are perceived to be [b]closely-related[/b] to their predecessors.

-[b]Closely-Related[/b]: A character's [b]non-rival Close Families[/b], [b]Spouses[/b], [b]Best Friends[/b] and [b]Soulmates[/b] are considered to be [b]closely-related[/b] to that character. In addition, their [b]heir's opinion of them[/b] also needs to be [b]greater than -30[/b] for them to be willing to take up the mantle.

-[b]Loosely-Related[/b]: An heir would be considered as [b]loosely-related[/b] to their predecessor if they are of the [b]same dynasty[/b] or are [b]extended families[/b] to each other. Those who would otherwise be considered [b]closely-related[/b] but [b]don't like their predecessor enough[/b] would also fall into this tier.
Loosely-related heirs are not favored/judged to the same extent. They would get [b]+10[/b] and [b]+20 opinion[/b] of their predecessor's [b]friends[/b] and [b]best friends[/b] respectively. Same logic for [b]rivals and nemesis[/b].

-[b]Unrelated[/b]: Those don't fit into the previous two tiers are viewed as unrelated to their predecessors. Their predecessor's relations [b]will not have an effect on them[/b].

[h1]🎭 Exceptions due to [b]Personality Traits[/b][/h1] 
[b]Nemesis[/b] and [b]Rivals[/b] with [b]forgiving[/b] trait will not become [b]rival[/b] or be marked as [b]potential rival[/b] on succession. However, [b]relevant opinion penalties still apply[/b].

